An odd three-ish step sequencer, placed inside of a metal elbow pipe. The "Made in Canada" stamp being visible in the final product is a bit of a happy accident, considering that this project was made during the height of the USA-Canada tariff wars.

A basic 555 LFO is fed into a CD4027 flip flop chip, wired up to light up a series of LEDs. These LEDs then affect a single light-dependent resistor. The resistance created by the LDR is output through the banana cables, which can be touched against any of the Screech instruments' touch points. The speed of the sequence can be adjusted, and the remaining potentiometers adjust the brightness of each LED, thus affecting the resulting resistance produced by the LDR. This circuit was paired up with a Durapro portable handcrank AM/FM radio, whose audio was routed through a 4051 chip, and whose solder points were outboarded to brass touch points--the resulting instrument is named the Baritone Screecher.
